SEC Planning Rulemaking
In Wake of ESign Legislation

The Securities and Exchange Commission announced Feb. 28 that it is planning=
=20
several rulemaking actions with respect to recordkeeping requirements in=20
light of the recently enacted Electronic Signatures in Global and National=20
Commerce Act--ESign.=20
ESign's record retention provisions will become effective June 1, the agency=
=20
advised.=20
In its release, the SEC noted that under the federal securities laws,=20
regulated entities--including broker-dealers, transfer agents, investment=20
companies, investment advisers, and public utility holding companies, must=20
keep certain records of their activities. According to the SEC, such entitie=
s=20
currently may keep certain records electronically, "subject to standards=20
designed to protect investors' interests, the financial stability of=20
regulated entities and generally to further the purposes of the federal=20
securities laws."=20

Remove Impediments

"ESign," the SEC continued, "is intended to remove unnecessary impediments t=
o=20
the use of electronic records in commerce, while preserving the ability of=20
agencies like the Commission to reconcile ESign's policy with the statutes=20
they administer." In its release, the agency said it plans shortly to provid=
e=20
interpretive guidance, and, where appropriate, "propose or adopt rules=20
consistent with ESign. These releases will be published separately in the=20
Federal Register," the commission noted.=20
It added that because ESign does not generally apply to information required=
=20
to be filed with government agencies, the commission is not currently=20
contemplating any changes to its existing filing rules as a result of ESign.=
=20
"Filers should therefore continue to follow current filing rules," the agenc=
y=20
advised.=20
